[7]Science as Folk

Shutdown letdown, but what’s next?

   image

   "We have the best government that money can buy."

   -Mark Twain

   Wasn’t this supposed to happen several months ago, but we somehow put
   aside our differences and made it work?  Oh right, we agreed not to
   think about it until later (which is now).  So NASA is out of funding,
   the CDC furloughed 8,754 workers (diseases have furloughed zero), and
   the NIH has stopped its research and halted new grants.  So it
   happened.  But do I dare ask, is this all bad?  (Yes, it’s bad, but
   stay with me here).  All day in the lab, I heard people complaining
   about missing online data sets and publications, government websites
   going down, grant reviews coming to a screeching halt, and job
   interviews at the NIH being up in the air.  Moreover, social media has
   been lighting up with people expressing how they didn’t realize how
   many government resources they needed just to get through their day
   conducting scientific research.

   image

   All of this has made me wonder, will this make scientists get involved
   in scientific policy?  The popular opinion is that science is becoming
   an increasingly prominent issue throughout the world.  Yet, most of the
   policies are dictated by people without technical training, and
   practicing scientists have been reluctant participants in the national
   conversation.  Rees Kassen of the University of Ottawa wrote an
   excellent [8]editorial in Nature about this very issue.  Kassen gives
   an example of the Canadian parliament.  Of the 308 members of
   parliament, 17 hold a degree in the natural sciences, engineering, or
   health sciences.  If these numbers reflected national university
   graduation rates, there would be 98 members of parliament with formal
   scientific training.  So the burden of nurturing the social momentum of
   science really falls on its practitioners.  Kassen states that,

   "researchers must recognize that poor scientific decisions in politics
   do not necessarily result from a lack of understanding. They are,
   rather, a failure of scientists to communicate their message
   effectively in what is ultimately a political, not a scientific arena."

   Moreover, Kassen goes on to point out a few interesting points of view
   that I think are true.  He asserts that,

   "scientists think too highly of their own view of the world and fail to
   appreciate the complex, multifarious nature of decision making."

   And also, that to a politician,

   "science is an interest group like any other."

   Kassen’s observations invoke a 2004 remark from former congressman
   Sherwood Boehlert, who was then the chair of the House Science
   Committee.  As he stated,

   "The argument that science funding is a long-term national investment
   does nothing to set scientists apart.  All that sets them apart is that
   scientists are the only group that thinks they’re making a unique
   argument."

   What a quote, eh?  It seems to confirm Kassen’s view that science is
   funded as an interest group.  So if the members of that group (the
   scientists) don’t voice strong displeasure and opposition against
   funding cuts, it might make it seem that we don’t really care about the
   cuts, doesn’t it? Many more have expressed this same view that
   scientists need to get involved in policy decisions.  I chose this one
   because it’s a gem.  If the Kassen piece didn’t grab you, how about
   a [9]plea by Newt Gingrich (of all people)!  Gingrich was a keynote
   speaker at the 2007 Society for Neuroscience Conference in San Diego (I
   was in the audience). Predictably, he was asked a lot of tough
   questions by the crowd, but his message was surprising.  He pleaded
   with the neuroscientists to get involved and help politician make
   informed decisions about scientific policy.  I don’t care much for the
   guy as a politician, but I found myself appreciating what he had to
   say.


   The shutdown is maddening and sad.  But if anything good comes out of
   this, I hope that it makes a generation of young scientists realize how
   much government support is require on a daily basis to accomplish
   science.  I hope it serves as a call to action to get involved and help
   politicians foster the policies that allow science in the United States
   to thrive.  I think it’s long overdue for the scientific community to
   start educating the public about the values of science, and make a case
   for the necessity of investing in its development.

