Nuclear Gastronomy

   image

   "The radiation left over from the Big Bang is the same as that in your
   microwave oven but very much less powerful. It would heat your pizza
   only to minus 271.3 degrees celsius - not much good for defrosting the
   pizza, let alone cooking it."

   -Stephen Hawking


   There have often been times in my career when I was stuck in the lab
   without any easy way of getting or making food.  This is the worst.  A
   long experiment (usually critical) makes for a long day.  But it’s even
   longer when you are hungry and irritable.  At these critical times, I
   found it’s useful to have a few non-perishable food items at work to
   make a quick meal with the resources available.  If anything, cooking
   in the lab makes for a few welcome minutes of distraction between
   experiments.  Here, I’ll periodically post some recipes that I’ve
   employed over the years.  Remember, all are laboratory-tested and
   scientist (at least this one) approved.

   The recipes for nuclear gastronomy follow a few rules:

   Rule #1: It must be tasty

   Rule #2: It must be tasty

   Rule #3: All ingredients must fit inside a coffee mug

   Rule #4: Everything must be cooked in a microwave

   Rule #5: Most of the recipe ingredients must be non-perishable (there
   maybe special exceptions)

   Rule #6: All recipes must take less than 15 minutes to prepare

   Mac and Cheese

   Ingredients:

   1/3 Cup pasta

   1/2 Cup water

   1/4 Cup milk, or 1 Tablespoon of instant dry milk

   1/4 Cup shredded cheddar cheese

   1) Combine the pasta and water in your mug.  Microwave on high at two
   minute intervals and stir the pasta between intervals.  Keep going
   until the water is absorbed and the pasta is soft (typically between 4
   - 6 minutes)

   Note: The water may boil over during the heating.  If this keeps
   happening, cut down the duration of the heating intervals.

   2) Add the milk and the cheese and microwave until the cheese is melted
   (typically about a minute).

   Note: If using powder milk: you may need to add a little water to
   dissolve the milk, and if you’re a biologist, I highly recommend that
   you NOT use the lab milk for western blotting.

   3) Stir and enjoy.
