Perhaps the worst day of scientific work. Ever.

   image

   Wheeler Peak, Nevada

   “Of all the trees we could have hit, we had to get the one that hits
   back!”

   -Ron Weasley, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets

   This story takes a bad day at work to a whole new level.  Donald Rusk
   Currey was a promising graduate student at the University of North
   Carolina at Chapel Hill.  His Ph.D. dissertation pioneered the use of
   dendrochronology techniques (looking at tree ring patterns) to study
   dynamic changes in the Earth’s climate.  In particular, Donald was
   interested in knowing what tree ring patterns could tell us about the
   cooling of the earth seen in Medieval times known as the [15]Little Ice
   Age.

   In 1963, Donald was a 30 year old scientist who became aware of a
   population of Bristlecone Pine trees on Wheeler peak. As Bristle cone
   pines in the White Mountains of California were discovered to be older
   than any species yet dated, Donald was particularly interested in
   taking core samples from these trees to see what they could tell us
   about past and current climate changes (rain amounts, temperature,
   etc).

   image

   Bristlecone Pine Tree

   In the summer of 1964, encouraged in his scientific pursuits by a grant
   from the National Science Foundation, Donald made a trip out to Nevada
   to obtain samples from the Bristlecone pines.  He climbed Wheeler peak
   and took several cores from trees on the mountain.  To his delight, he
   found that their ages exceed 3000 years (How cool is that!).  Donald
   became particularly captivated by one Bristlecone tree that had such a
   tortuous look that he hypothesized its age must surpass the ones he had
   already sampled.  He designated this tree WPN-114, and dug in with his
   specialized hand-powered drill purchased from Sweden.  Immediately, he
   noticed that obtaining a core sample from WPN-114 was very difficult.
   (Ping!) His first attempt caused the drill bit to break in the trunk of
   the tree.  When he started a second bore in the trunk with his backup
   drill, (Ping!) the second drill bit also broke in the tree.  Out of
   tools and dejected, Donald hiked back down the peak.  At this point,
   Donald was frantic.  He knew this was the only trip he would make to
   Nevada that year, and worse, all of his tools needed for data
   collection were now stuck inside the trunk of a tree.  His trip out
   west appeared to be in jeopardy.

   In desperation, Donald located the district forest ranger office and
   explained his situation.  Surprisingly, the forest rangers told him not
   to worry.  Since Donald’s tree was not a notable landmark, they would
   cut the tree down for him.  On August 6, 1964, Donald and the forest
   rangers climbed up Wheeler peak and down went WPN-114, and Donald was
   able to obtain several slabs of the tree to take back with him.  He
   began to manually count of the rings.  After the first day, Donald was
   able to count 1000 rings, putting him in medieval times…

   Day 2…2000 (Jesus times)

   Day 3…3000 (David and Goliath times)

   Day 4…4844 (End of the Neolithic era)!

   At this point, Donald paused. He realized he had in his possession the
   remnants of a 4844 year old organism.  Until then, the oldest living
   thing ever recorded had been another tree dated at 4600 years.  Imagine
   the panic Donald Rusk must have felt at realizing that he just killed
   the oldest living thing known to man.  Staying true to his scientific
   training, Donald counted again, and again, but to no avail.  Every
   count showed that Donald had in his possession the remnants of the
   oldest living life form on the planet. Moreover, the locals and tree
   aficionados were inclined to naming the Bristlecone pines in the area.
    And ironically, WPN-114 wasn’t a nameless landmark, it was known as
   the Prometheus tree, after the mythological champion of mankind who
   stole fire from the gods to give to humans.

   image

   Donald R. Currey (1965) Ecology

   So imagine yourself in this situation.  You’re 30, on your way to a
   Ph.D., and feeling good about finally creating a professional
   reputation for yourself.  Then you come to the realization that in your
   enthusiasm, you annihilated the oldest thing to inhabit this planet.
   What do you do?  Despite all of the irony already embedded in this
   story, what makes this story truly remarkable is what Donald Currey did
   next.  He published his data.  I think it would be completely
   understandable if Donald pretended this never happened, or reported the
   tree as having fewer rings than in reality.  But Donald stuck to the
   truth.  He published his findings in the journal Ecology in 1965, and I
   think it’s fair to say that he knew that his ‘work’ would cause an
   uproar.  For example, the Little Ice Age is attributed to have occurred
   between ~1350 - 1850 A.D., but in the paper, Donald attributes the era
   to be from 2000 years ago to the present.  Presumably, in an attempt to
   soften the criticism of why he was taking samples from such old trees
   in the first place.  Despite this, Donald went through with the hard
   thing.  He told the truth and accurately reported his findings even
   though he knew it threatened to destroy his budding career and
   scientific reputation.


   As you can imagine, there was a lot of public anger in the years
   following its publication.  Donald never talked publicly about the
   Prometheus tree.  But despite the magnitude of his error (and perhaps
   because of his intellectual courage), Donald continued to pursue
   science.  He earned his Ph.D. from the University of Kansas in 1969 and
   went on to have a fruitful academic career as a professor at the
   University of Utah, where he continued his work with Bristlecone pines
   in the Great Basin.  He became a well respected scientist and a
   champion of environmental issues. When it came time to protect the
   Bristlecone pines, Donald personally lobbied Congress to designate the
   Great Basin as a national park. Donald passed away in 2004 at the age
   of 70.  The University of Utah department of Geography has endowed a
   scholarship in his name.
