The most human pursuit of human pursuits

   image

   “And Lot’s wife, of course, was told not to look back where all those
   people and their homes had been.  But she did look back, and I love her
   for that, because it was so human.  So she was turned into a pillar of
   salt.  So it goes.”

   -Kurt Vonnegut, Slaughterhouse-Five

   Kurt Vonnegut was referring to the Biblical story of Lot from the Book
   of Genesis.  Lot and Sarah were spared from the destruction of Sodom
   and Gomorrah, and on the orders of God, were explicitly told not to
   look back while fleeing God’s destruction of those cities.  Of course,
   curiosity got the best of Sarah, and so she looked back and was
   punished by transforming into a pillar of salt.  This is the story
   that’s stayed with me throughout my scientific career.  Not because I’m
   religious (I’m not), or because I read the Bible (I don’t.  Okay, my
   parents made me a long time ago), but because embedded in this ancient
   story is the paradoxical nature of what it is to be human.  On the one
   hand, we’re hopelessly inept creatures who can’t obey a simple command,
   on the other hand, we’re fiercely curious beings willing to pursue
   knowledge despite the consequences.  Quite simply, science is an
   entirely human endeavor, and arguably, it is THE most human of human
   activities.  It is conducted by imperfect creatures struggling with
   confusion, errors, emotions, and temptations.  It shouldn’t work, but
   miraculously, it does and it thrives.  Science works because of two
   beautiful cogs within our being: our willingness to fail (repeatedly),
   and above all else, our insatiable curiosity.

   So that’s pretty much all I’m going to say about the obvious: the
   pursuit of scientific truth is in our DNA (no pun intended).  The drive
   to fulfill our curiosity reflects some of the very best of what it is
   to be human.  But I’m really here to illustrate the parts of science
   that make you cringe, shake your head, and hopefully make you see that
   science is really a collection of genuine but flawed humans trying
   their best.  This blog is dedicated to telling the stories in science
   that reveal more about our humanity than about science (hence, “science
   as folk”).

   This seems like a good place to start.  Recently, I read a great piece
   by John Skylar entitled “[18]Why you DON’T actually fucking love
   science”.  In it, John makes the point that science is produced by
   people who endure years of sacrifice, especially in the face of federal
   budget cuts toward scientific research.  For example, a staple source
   of funding for biomedical research in academia is grants awarded to
   professors by the National Institutes of Health (NIH), the RO1 grant.
   As John put it, this is the “I made it” grant, and it is the money that
   pays for the supplies, equipment, laboratory space, and the salaries of
   people doing the research.

   The following is a graph provided by the NIH that shows a sharp
   increase starting in the last 10 years or so for the average age of a
   FIRST time recipient (that’s right, first time).  Mind you, these are
   scholars who have invested 4 years to complete a bachelor’s degree in
   science, ~6 years to complete their Ph.D., and ~5 years of postdoctoral
   training (and that’s pretty much the minimum).  Why is it going up?

   NIH-Graph

   Source: National Institutes of Health

   Good question.  The answer is in the NIH budget.  The amount of money
   the NIH has to give out has stagnated and slowly decreased in the last
   10 years.

   image

   Source: Adapted from [19]John Skylar with data from the [20]Federation
   of American Societies for Experimental Biology

   So let’s pause for a minute and think about the implications of this.
   The pot of money that funds scientific careers has dwindled over the
   last ten years, and this has pushed the age at which scientists start
   their independent careers into the 40’s.  Admittedly, this sounds bad.
   But scientists are a plucky bunch lacking any emotions, so they should
   be able to handle this disappointment without letting it affect their
   work, right?  Well, let’s look at some additional data.  One of the
   worst things that can happen to a scientist is a retraction of their
   work.  Scientific journals reserve the right to publicly strike a paper
   out of existence if the work is proven to have errors that change the
   conclusions of that paper at a later date (i.e., fabrication of data,
   incorrect analysis, etc.).  As science has grown, the number of papers
   that have been retracted has also increased.

   image

   Source: [21]Steen RG, Casadevall, A, Fang FC. PLOS One (2013)

   Importantly, these increases don’t just reflect an overall rise in the
   number of retractions, but the percentage of publications that have
   been retracted has dramatically increased in the past few years.  So
   we’re seeing a real acceleration in the number of retractions in the
   literature.

   Is the increase in difficulty of attaining and maintaining a career in
   science related to the recent increase in the number of retractions?
   Let’s see what happens when we combine the two previous graphs.

   image

   It sure seems suspicious, doesn’t it?  On a human level, this makes a
   lot of sense.  Scientific research has been contracting in the United
   States , and these are desperate times for a lot of folks.  Indeed, the
   wavering support of science by the federal government leaves a lot to
   be desired, and in the end will hinder scientific progress.  But before
   I make it sound like science is going to the crooks, it’s critical that
   I mention a few things to this discussion.  Science works through a
   collective test of time.  What I mean is that once a theory is
   proposed, the scientific community goes to work to test this theory
   through their own experimentation.  Reproducible results are confirmed
   and irreproducible results are discarded, thus producing a body of
   scientific knowledge through the action of group intelligence.  This is
   a critical aspect of scientific discovery.  So although the rate of
   retractions is surely increasing, the dramatic increase in the last few
   years may not truly reflect a substantial increase in deceptive
   practices.  Indeed, due to several high profile cases of scientific
   fraud in the past decade, journals have increased their efforts to weed
   out fraudulent work.  So some of this increase in the number of
   retractions simply reflects better methods to detect errors, or put in
   a more positive light, science is evolving better methods of
   self-correction.  But needless to say, the very fact that the
   scientific community needs to divert already limited resources to
   detect increasing amounts of fraudulent work serves to further limit
   our progress.

   I also want to point out a couple more things that speaks to the
   honesty of the scientific community.  First, not all retractions
   reflect fraud or data fabrication.  In many cases, papers are retracted
   because of genuine errors, and often times, the papers are retracted
   voluntarily by the investigators once they realize their mistakes.  For
   an example, see [22]here.  And perhaps most importantly, the number of
   retracted papers represents just a tiny fraction of scientific
   publications produced each year.  Between 1973 and 2011, 21.2 million
   journal articles were published according to PubMed.  Of those, 890
   articles were retracted, producing a retraction rate of 1 in 23,799
   articles, or about 0.004%.  Compare that to an error rate of ~2% for
   the U.S. Postal Service, and it looks pretty good.  This is perhaps the
   most impressive part of all of this.  There are a few bad apples out
   there for sure, but despite all of the hardships endured by
   researchers, and the sad state of scientific funding, science continues
   to hold its integrity.  In short, science is almost entirely composed
   of honest people working hard to produce innovative work on a daily
   basis.  Kind of makes you feel good about human nature and for the
   future of our species, doesn’t it?
